    <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Self-Evaluations</h1>
        <div class="border-b-4 border-b-gray-700 pb-4">
            <h2>Dec 2022 — March 2023</h2>
            <h3>Self Evaluation of Performance of Responsibilities & Annual Goals</h3>
            <p>
                I’m very thankful for all the opportunities I had working with the WebUX team, DDaS team, and the Collaborative Community Review team this year. I believe that the massive projects that we undertook would immensely improve the user experience of our patrons on several digital applications that we offer. I continued to  collaborate with departments within the library such as the Makerspace to overhaul the MakeAtState application and teams outside of the Library such as MSU IT to integrate the MakeAtState application with OKTA, an identity management system offered by MSU IT. I’m fortunate to have colleagues and student employees eager to participate in UX testing activities which helped me organize and moderate UX testing on the new Library website. In addition, I collaborated with the WebUX team to develop the new MSU Library website and other projects that are handled by the team on a daily basis.
            </p>
            <h4>Main Website Redesign & Migration</h4>
            <p>
                The WebUX team is helming the redesign and development of the Main Library website which gave the opportunity to closely work with all the team members and pull my weight towards the completion of the project. As a part of this project, under the guidance of our team I took lead in developing the Main Library Search, Main Library Homepage, and Branch Library Homepages in late fall of 2023.
            </p>
            <p>
                Development of the Main Library Search had its own set of challenges as we decided to make our search module configurable by non developers from the start. This enables all Drupal admins to set the number of results per box, set the results box title, show or remove a results box from the display, set the results box order, etc. New functionality was added where users can view results from a single source without being overwhelmed by the bento box view. EDS and FOLIO API’s were leveraged to bring in the call number and availability of books and e-books at the request of our librarians and this data is presented to the viewers in a usable manner. Additional challenges were encountered when the Springshare API wasn’t able to search Databases which were overcome by writing a Drupal module that fetches all the Databases from Springshare and indexes into our backend search engine SOLR. This functionality has also been extended to Course Reserves where the data fetched from the FOLIO API’s is indexed into our backend search engine. This helped us enable features like keyword highlighting, searching by course number, instructor name, course name, etc. Boolean searches were also enabled, further improving the functionality over the existing search. Development of the search was wrapped up in December 2022 and passed onto our Web Advisory Group for testing in January 2023.
            </p>
            <p>
                I started focusing on developing the Main Library homepage as it was one of my goals for the year– this included Quick links, Events & Workshops, News, Exhibits, and the What’s going on sections. The  Events & Workshops, News, Exhibits section had us pull data from external sources such as Springshare events; this led to writing a new Drupal module that has the ability to to fetch events from Springshare. This was further improved where the module can filter events by categories. Both News and Exhibits were built inside Drupal and the What’s going on section contained featured items from News and Exhibits. Wrapping up our homepage in January 2023, I moved on to building out the Murray & Hong Special Collections homepage, Creative Solutions Center homepage, and the Makerspace homepage by February 2023.
            </p>
            <h4>UX Testing for the Main Website</h4>
            <p>
                As we entered February 2023, the WebUX team completed development of several major pieces of the main website such as Main Library Homepage, Hours pages, Main Library search, News, Events & Workshops, Exhibits, etc. It was time for us to start UX testing on the new site.
            </p>
            <p>
                This was our first foray into UX Testing and I took this opportunity to accomplish another goal of mine for the year– developing and administering a UX test. The prime focus of the UX testing process was to identify any pain points that users might experience while performing specific tasks on the new website. This process also entails analyzing the reasons behind the pain points, and guiding the development by providing actionable insights to address the issues.
            </p>
            <p>
                I collaborated with Joshua Sanchez and Shelby Kroske to identify several UX research and testing methodologies that we could employ to gain insights on how patrons will use our new site. The methods that were identified are User Journey Mapping, which involves observing users when they are performing a task, Five Second Tests, which involves gathering first impressions on the site, and Heuristic Analysis which is to measure the usability of our site against a set of predefined criteria. We started our UX testing with User Journey Mapping research activity.
            </p>
            <p>
                We were fortunate enough to have eager participants from the library faculty, staff, and student employees. We took turns administering the research activity where our participants were asked to perform a series of tasks on the homepage, hours pages, search pages, and events pages– they were asked to think out loud while performing the tasks. The steps taken to perform the tasks, their feelings, and opportunities for improvement were recorded in a collaborative workspace called Miro. This research activity was performed with12 participants and we are planning to invite students to this activity in the week March 20th. This activity helped us identify a few places on the new website that need improvements and we are thrilled about our findings. We are enthusiastic about making these improvements and streamline our UX testing process.
            </p>
            <h4>MakeAtState Application Redesign and Migration</h4>
            <p>
                Makerspace uses 3DPrime, an application written in PHP back in 2018 to support both the patrons and Makerspace staff to submit and print 3D models. As the years progressed the application was getting outdated in terms of design and the underlying technology. Jamie Moriarty, our Makerspace Coordinator requested an overhaul of the application, reimagining the 3D print submission workflow process. 
            </p>
            This project was on a tight schedule to complete and had external dependencies such as communicating with Central IT to use MSU’s OKTA  identity management system. One of the initial steps to ensure the success of this project was to update the underlying technologies such as migrating to a newer version of PHP, updating the underlying theme to Bootstrap5 which gave the application a new look, and using current DevOps practices such as Doker & Docker Swarm along with traefik which makes the deployment and maintenance a smooth sailing process. 
            <p>
                The next step was to work closely with Jamie Moriarty to bring her vision to life. This included removing the existing job submission workflow and building a new workflow that supports adding multiple files into a project and submitting them as one job. This feature was a massive improvement to the user experience of our patrons which enabled them to have multiple items in a print job, mimicking some of the most popular ecommerce sites like Amazon. 
            </p>
            <p>
                This also resulted in changes to the staff workflow on how these jobs with multiple files should be handled. A creative solution was implemented where the staff who are processing these requests can see all the files in a job and set the prices for each of the files individually. The application then calculates  the total price and notifies the user via email. The patron can then accept the price which is when the printing begins or can request the staff to modify the job and files in the job as needed.
            </p>
            <p>
                This project also needed integration with MSU’s identity management system. MSU uses OKTA to authenticate affiliated users which gave me an opportunity to collaborate with Jami Baker from Central IT and integrate OKTA authentication into the MakeAtState application. This allows patrons to use their MSU credentials to login to the site and submit their print jobs. This change also involves figuring out the logout system where an option will be provided to the patron to just logout of the MakeAtState application or logout of all MSU applications at once. Finally I collaborated with Renee McConahy who assisted in setting up the production servers and helped us get past the finish line and launch the application for public use.
            </p>
            <h4>Additional Work</h4>
            <p>
                In addition to the projects discussed above I worked closely with the CCR (Collaborative Community Review) team to develop the Pilcrow application. My collaboration with the team ended in December 2022. Other regular duties of mine include supporting our library staff and faculty to update their web pages, add additional features to the existing library website and the intranet site, maintenance of the MakeAtState application, providing analytics data as requested by our staff and faculty, and supporting Systems unit to pull data from the FOLIO API as needed. 
            </p>
