            <h2>2023 — 2024</h2>
            <h3>Self Evaluation of Performance of Responsibilities & Annual Goals</h3>
            <p>
                The last 12 months have been a cluster of great learning opportunities, milestones, and collaborations with units and organizations internal and external to the MSU Libraries. I’m very thankful for the opportunities that I had working with WebUx and Accessibility teams on a myriad of projects, achieving some important milestones both personally and for the Library. Projects that I worked on this year included close collaboration with various units and branches within the library to overhaul their web presence, making them more usable and accessible, and building out the discovery layers for each of the units. I’m grateful for my colleagues who were enthusiastic to build a comprehensive and sustainable UX research/testing process for all the digital platforms built by the WebUx team–which included coming up creative ways to recruit participants, gather feedback, make recommendations and implement improvements to the MSU Library main website and MakeAtState applications on a monthly cycle. This year I had the opportunity to join the Accessibility team which provided me with opportunities  to investigate assistive technologies and testing softwares. This process led to closely working with a great team to make iterative improvements to several digital interfaces built or purchased by the Library.
            </p>
            <h4>Main Website Redesign, Migration, & Launch</h4>
            <p>
                Our team spearheaded the design development and launch of the MSU Libraries’ main website. It was a 2+ year project and the site was launched in August 2023. As a part of this massive project, with the help of my team, I took a lead in developing the homepages, search & discovery layer, alerts, events and news  sections for all the units in the Library. This involved closely working with unit heads, assessing their requirements–especially for developing the unit specific search which can be easily customizable using the Drupal admin interface, and adding the ability to post unit specific news to their homepages. This also included developing a mobile version of the homepages for all the units in the library and setting up the alerts system which can be targeted to specific branches, a notification indicator that can be used to view branch specific alerts on their respective pages.
                I had the opportunity to collaborate with Shelby Krose and Shelbie Vilag to do some UX research and completely reimagine the Library Spaces interface. Taking inspiration from some of our peer institutions we developed a new interface to feature all the spaces offered by the MSU Libraries. This provides our patrons with a myriad of filters to precisely identify and reserve a space that suits their needs. This interface also provides options to add new spaces to the system, easily search them, and works across all devices. As we crossed our 6 month mark of launching our website, this new interface has been used 17,064 times. Our analytics indicate that this is one of the most viewed pages from our homepage. 
            </p>
            <p>
                I took the lead on developing/migrating the new interface for MSU Libraries Little Cookbooks collection, a Grant project from Shirley Sliker. Her wishes for keeping the original look and feel of the site was taken into consideration and honored, while overhauling the search interface, adding additional functionality to add and remove filters, and building functionality on the individual record page to browse items from the same publisher or brand. This site is usable on all device types providing identical functionality across all screen sizes.
            </p>
            <p>
                As we are getting close to Beta Launch, which was scheduled for July 2023, I exported all data from Google Analytics from our legacy sites, set up our new Analytics platform Matomo to track visits from our new beta site. This new analytics platform has been extremely helpful in tracking usage on how our patrons are discovering our site, what search engines they are using to find us, the transactions they make on our site, and the external sites they visit from the MSU Libraries website. A problem that we ran into in the days following our launch was that we did account for the amount of load on the servers, which led to some slow loading pages. Our analytics tool indicated that our avg load time on the day of launch was 5.66s. We were able to quickly jump on the problem and with the help form our friendly folks from the Systems unit we were able to quickly get our pages to load faster. Currently our average page load time, counting all 6 months worth of data,  for the homepage is 2.33s.
            </p>
            <p>
                With all aforementioned exciting moments, our new library site was launched on August 17th, 2023. We have made numerous ux and accessibility improvements to the site along with adding new features, constantly taking feedback from the community and quickly acting on them to squash any bugs and improve the user experience. I was also able to extend some of the improvements we made ro our Springshare products such as LibGuides and our Bookings system to keep the look and feel consistent among all our sites.
            </p>
            <h4>Redesign of Digital Media Lending Site</h4>
            <p>
                Another massive undertaking was the design and development of the theme for the MSU Digital Media Lending site. This is an open-source project named Avalon, developed by Indiana University, Bloomington–used to ingest digital media for patrons to borrow. This application is written in Ruby on Rails, which was a completely new language for me. With the help from my colleagues Shelby Kroske and Shel Vilag, I developed a new MSU Libraries theme for the Avalon code base. This involved us meeting with the IU Bloomington team on a monthly basis, who were a huge help and guided us navigating a new framework. Our team was able to successfully develop the theme for all pages across site, understand the ingest process, and we are working closely with our colleagues from the Systems unit to launch the production site with the MSUL theme hosted on Amazon Web Services.
            </p>
            <h4>Creating & Executing UX Research/Testing Process</h4>
            <p>
                We began our UX Research/Testing on the main website in the early stages of development. This led to the creation of a robust and sustainable research and testing process to evaluate the usability of the interfaces we are building. My colleagues Austin Deneau, Shelby Kroske and Joshua Sanchez are very enthusiastic about this aspect of the development life cycle. We were able to conduct UX testing on a monthly basis–coming up with creative ways to recruit participants and procuring incentives for folks who are interested in participating in our testing process.
            </p>
            <p>
                We worked closely with all the branch library heads to identify the core functions of their website and created UX tasks around these core functions. The tasks included asking the participants to perform an action, with minimal instruction, and observing and documenting their journey, their feelings, and what they think can be improved to enhance the user experience while performing the tasks. This UX research technique is called User Journey Mapping and used to identify pain points navigating digital interfaces. We identified that our participants are having trouble using the links in the header region on all branch homepages and pointed out that the pages looked too similar where they weren't sure if the page belonged to the main library or one of the branches.
            </p>
            <p>
                We developed multiple Search and Spaces interfaces to perform some A/B testing, which included showing our participants different versions of the same functionality, directly comparing them and documenting how they respond to each version. As a result we updated our search to pull results from 7 different sources which are now displayed in scrollable bento boxes. Our participants pointed out that there was no easy way to get back to the spaces page, after viewing a single page. This led to the addition of a persistent button on all the individual space pages. We also altered the look of the filters, added a clear all filters button and some help text based on the recommendations. These are just some of the numerous other minor and major changes we made to the main library website directly based on the feedback from the UX testing process.
            </p>
            <h4>Evaluating Assistive Technology & Testing Softwares</h4>
            <p>
                This year I joined the Accessibility team which provided me with opportunities to evaluate and use assistive technologies and accessibility testing tools. I received a copy of Rocket Core reusable smart notebook and pen–which can be used by students to OCR the notes using the accompanying phone app. The assignment was to evaluate the efficacy of these books and pens so they can be put in circulation for the students to use. Our testing surfaced some problems with accompanying software as well as some logistical problems that may arise using these in circulation. With the help of Heidi Schroeder we were able to gain the axe-core pro subscription, which was used to identify accessibility issues that cannot be detected by automatic a11y testing tools. My colleague Austin Deneau and I share the license; we use it to find and fix a11y issues on the main website, Springshare products and other applications built by MSU Libraries.
            </p>
            <h4>Improving Accessibility of Springshare Products</h4>
            <p>
                MSU Libraries uses a plethora of Springshare products such as LibGuides, LibCal, LibAnswers, LibChat, etc. I identified the list of most used pages in LibGuides which was sent to folks at University of Tennessee, Knoxville for evaluation. After we received the report detailing the a11y issues from UTK, Austin Deneau and I scheduled a working meeting to identify potential fixes and implement them in the Springshare system for LibGuides. Our student employees worked on a similar evaluation for the LibCal system and we are in the process of applying fixes wherever we can and documenting suggestions for Springshare.
            </p>
            <h4>Accessibility Website Redesign</h4>
            <p>
                I collaborated with Austin Deneau, Zoë McLaughlin, and Heidi Schroeder to craft a new Accessibility Statement for the MSU Libraries, and overhaul the Accessibility site on the main library website. We focused our efforts on making it easy for our patrons to contact the accessibility team members, find information about the accessibility of our physical and digital spaces and improve the navigation of the site. 
