            <h4>Turfgrass Information Center Website Redesign, Migration & Launch</h4>
            <p>
                As Drupal 7 was approaching the end of life on Jan 5th, 2025 we had tight and immovable deadline to build the new Turfgrass Information Website (https://tic.lib.msu.edu/) using a newer version of the Content Management System (Drupal 10). Under the leadership of Joshua Schanez, I spearheaded the efforts to build the application stack using some cutting edge technologies such as Traefik, a reverse proxy server that helps with url routing. This also made it easy to defend ourselves from numerous bot attacks that targeted our Main website and TIC website. The application stack was also improved from what we had in the previous years which made it easy to share the same code base and build different developer, test, and production instances of the site with relative ease.
            </p>
            <p>
                Establishing the application stack laid the groundwork for the project, while the core focus of the project was to build the numerous search interfaces that search the STAR backend database that the Turfgrass Information Center uses. Shelby Kroske, our lead designer led the efforts to design the new search interfaces and with the direction they provided I built the Basic, Power, Guided, and Thesaurus searches on the new TIC website. The Power and Guided searches, especially saw significant improvements from the old system providing the users abilities to add and remove search terms and group search terms together. The result selection functionality–which allows users to save a set of results also saw significant upgrades as in the count of selected results is updated dynamically and results being pulled from the correct backend database when a user switches between search types.
            </p>
            <p>
                I spearheaded the efforts to align the search design with Shelby's vision, ensuring it met the designer's intended aesthetic and functionality. This ensured that our TIC site was functional, usable and aesthetically pleasing for desktop, tablet and mobile users. Presenting the TIC information on a small screen was a challenge that we overcame by closely collaborating with Andrew and Elizabeth to ensure that it is meeting their needs.
            </p>
            Our new TIC site was launched on Jan 6th, 2025 and for the first time we added analytics to the site. This will allow us to track usage on the site, help us identify which searches are popular and the devices that our users use to perform the searches. So far we have 5,529 visits to the site with 44,759 page views and 20,672 unique page views. We also had some unprompted praise from USGA who said “Hadn’t been TGIF in a while, new website look great, and behaves well! Nice work.”.
            </p>
            <h4>UX Research for ILS</h4>
            <p>
                The ILS unit engaged our team to redesign their homepage and enhance the information architecture, ensuring that content is easily accessible and discoverable. The ILS team also helped us identify a list of users, both internal and external to the library. Our team, consisting of Austin D., Shel V., Shelby K., and myself, conducted interviews with ILS users as part of a User Journey Mapping exercise. This UX research activity aimed to identify pain points within the site and improve the user experience. Through our research, we uncovered several significant issues.
            </p>
            <p>
                Firstly, patrons found the various terminologies used on the site—such as ILS, ILL, Getit@MSU, and Getthis— is confusing, leading to uncertainty about their meanings and purposes. Additionally, users struggled to determine the appropriate navigation process for requesting materials through the ILS system.
            </p>
            <p>
                We also identified multiple design challenges. For instance, the tabs on the ILS homepage lacked clarity, making it unclear whether they were clickable. Furthermore, the branding on the ILLiad system was inconsistent with the main website, creating a disjointed user experience. These findings highlighted critical areas for improvement and will be guiding our efforts to build a more intuitive and cohesive ILS site this summer.
            </p>
            <h4>Digital Signage Application Development</h4>
            <p>
                Our team had been utilizing FourWinds, a vendor product, to power the building’s digital signage. However, the system was plagued with software bugs and lacked critical features. For instance, it failed to display hours of operation and persisted in showing outdated maps on the screens, even though the correct maps had been uploaded into the system. These ongoing frustrations motivated us to develop a custom, in-house solution for digital signage.
            </p>
            <p>
                Shelby Kroske spearheaded the design of the new Digital Signage system, while Austin Denau and I focused on its development. Together, we identified the need for a Progressive Web App (PWA) that could self-update and refresh content at regular intervals. This venture pushed us into uncharted territory, requiring us to learn new technologies. We adopted Angular, a well-known web framework for building PWAs, and also ventured into Python development for the first time to create the backend of the application.
            </p>
            <p>
                The new system includes functionality for making API calls to retrieve calendar events for various rooms throughout the building, as well as to fetch operating hours and event details for both the main building and its branches. It boasts a refreshed look and enhanced features, such as the ability to display accurate, real-time data on screens, updated building information, and scalability to accommodate additional screens as needed. The redesigned Digital Signage system, which represents a significant technological leap for our team, is set to launch on March 31, 2025. We are hopeful that the new system is more reliable, functional, and provides a memorable experience for building occupants and visitors alike
            </p>
            <h4>Evaluating Main Library Website for the New Title II Requirements</h4>
            <p>
                The updated Title II requirements under the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) emphasize digital accessibility for state, local governments and affiliated institutions. These regulations mandate that websites, mobile apps, and digital content comply with WCAG 2.1 AA standards to ensure accessibility for individuals with disabilities. 
            </p>
            <p>
                In response to these requirements, under the leadership of Heidi Schroeder, Austin Denau and I developed a prototype application using Python and JavaScript. The application was designed to evaluate web pages for WCAG 2.2 AA compatibility. It runs on a designated set of pages, identifies accessibility violations, and generates a spreadsheet detailing the errors. We applied this prototype to all 1,378 pages of the Main Library website, successfully identifying a list of accessibility (A11Y) issues across the site.
            </p>
            <p>
                Additionally, the MSU Office of Civil Rights conducted a manual review of a smaller subset of the website and provided us with a categorized list of issues. Their findings overlapped with the results from our prototype and were grouped into Critical, Significant, and Minor violations. To date, we have resolved all but one of the Critical violations, addressed most of the Significant violations, and corrected a few Minor violations. I’m committed to continuing these efforts until the site achieves full compliance with Title II requirements, ensuring a more accessible and inclusive experience for all users.
            </p>
